As an introverted creative individual who is self-employed and very privacy-conscious, running a business shouldn't feel so awkward, but sometimes it does. Most online resources and mentors tell you to be extroverted when dealing with large (evil) tech companies. Advertise here, follow the algorithms, share your charm. Get verified on that service, be online all day, answer questions with your own videos, and respond immediately. Videos, videos, and more videos.
1/3
This year is my year of transformation.
I don't want to continue giving my money, data, and energy to large tech companies, nor do I want to listen to mentors who only apply a single extroverted solution to everyone. I'm exploring new business models while also working to overcome my long-held belief that only by doing things in a certain specific way can one succeed.
Good luck to me!
The first step has been taken.
I left FB, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and logged out of my personal WhatsApp account.
Yesterday, I also removed the last external tracker from my website - Google Analytics, and felt great about it.
To better support GDPR, I recently subscribed to a European CRM service and will migrate my business there over the next few weeks.
I transferred my MX records to Proton, and now have full SPF, DKIM, and DMARC, without having to pay Google for basic email verification anymore.
3/3
